From John Switzer Frame Subject Re CMOS Checksum error In article Michael Cook writes Recently I have been getting a CMOS Checksum error when I first turn on my It doesn't happen everytime I turn it on nor can I predict when it is going to I have an AMI BIOS and all of the setting are lost for example the drive types and the password However the date and time remain If anyone knows what can be causing this please let me Most likely reason is that your backup battery is failing this battery maintains the contents of the CMOS memory when AC power is turned off and if the battery is flakey then the contents of the CMOS will be lost and the checksum will be wrong along with most other of the CMOS data Try replacing the If however your PC doesn't use a battery but a large capacitor to power the CMOS you should check to see if you can replace the capacitor with a more normal lithium If this isn't possible make sure you leave your PC on for a half hour or hour each day this will keep the capacitor I'd opt for the battery change It's also possible but unlikely that a rogue problem or even a virus is corrupting the If your battery seems okay get a virus scanner and check out your